    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-11-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-11-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="849"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d849">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/1840</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-11-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 4, 1915, noon.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 2 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3154. Paragraph numbered 13, beginning on <ref target="#pg_10">page 10</ref> of
                        note,<note n="1" xml:id="d849fn1">The note of October 21, <hi rend="italic"
                            >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_578">p. 578</ref>.</note> is not quite
                    clear to me. If it means that the British Government has, as a deliberate
                    Government policy, increased or will increase British trade at the expense of
                    American trade, such an imputation of bad faith has been repeatedly denied by
                    the British Government.</p>
                <p>It occurs to me respectfully to ask whether this be your meaning, and if so,
                    whether the paragraph shall be sent in as it was.</p>
                <p>In view of repeated British denials of foregoing as a Government policy, I wish
                    to be absolutely certain of your meaning, and therefore risk the small delay
                    that this question entails.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
